President Joe Biden has announced his intent to nominate several individuals to serve as key leaders in his Administration. These nominations include:

1. Nelson W. Cunningham as Deputy United States Trade Representative. Cunningham co-founded McLarty Associates and has extensive experience in foreign policy and political matters.

2. James R. Ives as Inspector General of the Department of the Treasury. Ives is a career member of the Senior Executive Service and currently serves as the Principal Deputy Director of the Defense Criminal Investigative Service.

3. Stephen Ravas as Inspector General of the Corporation for National and Community Service. Ravas joined the Corporation for National and Community Service Office of the Inspector General as Counsel to the Inspector General in 2019.

4. Leonardo Martinez-Diaz as United States Executive Director of the International Bank for Reconstruction and Development. Martinez-Diaz is currently the Managing Director for Climate Finance in the Office of the Special Presidential Envoy for Climate at the U.S. Department of State.

5. Anne Marie Wagner as a Member of the Federal Labor Relations Authority. Wagner has been Associate Special Counsel with the Office of Special Counsel since 2015 and previously served as Vice Chairman of the Merit Systems Protection Board.

The White House will also continue renominating candidates whose nominations were returned to the President at the end of the first session of the 118th Congress. Today's transmission to the Senate includes 16 renominations, and more renominations will be transmitted in the coming weeks. The White House hopes the Senate will take action expeditiously on these nominations.